<p><strong>Free Mobile Voice, Text and Data Plans Coming to UK</strong></p>
<p><em>[BBC]</em></p>
<p>US company FreedomPop is to extend its <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-32704051">free mobile data, voice and text</a> offering to the UK from July, after its equivalent US service attracted more than half a million users.&nbsp; FreedomPop will offer Sim cards that offer 200MB of data, 200 texts and 200 minutes of voice calls per month using the cellular network at no cost.&nbsp; The firm, which is backed by Skype founder Niklas Zennstom, says it will make money by selling extra services.&nbsp; These include the ability to roll over unused data to the next month, anonymous browsing to protect online privacy, and the ability to add a second phone number from more than 60 countries so that friends and family outside the UK can call at local rates.</p>
<p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
<p><strong>Shorts</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Windows 10&rsquo;s new browser (previously project Spartan) will be called <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2015/04/29/microsofts-new-browser-will-be-called-microsoft-edge">Microsoft Edge</a>.&nbsp; [TechCrunch]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Education Week features a special report on <a href="http://www.edweek.org/ew/collections/blended-learning-special-report-2015/index.html">blended learning in K-12 education</a>.&nbsp; [Education Week]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>See how a panel of experts reacted to five <a href="http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/5-ed-tech-ideas-face-the-chronicles-version-of-shark-tank/56511">&lsquo;Dragon&rsquo;s Den&rsquo; pitches for ed tech products</a> at a recent conference.&nbsp; [The Chronicle]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Amazon has <a href="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3072252/Amazon-makes-toy-department-gender-neutral-Boy-girl-search-filter-removed.html">removed the &lsquo;boy&rsquo; and &lsquo;girl&rsquo; options</a> from its online menu for searching and buying toys.&nbsp; [Daily Mail]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The Online Learning Consortium and MERLOT have merged their two journals which will now be known as <a href="https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/04/22/merlot-olc-merge-scholarly-journals">Online Learning</a>.&nbsp; [Audrey Watters]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>300m <a href="http://thenextweb.com/twitter/2015/04/18/twitter-updates-privacy-policy-for-non-us-accounts-and-moves-jurisdiction-to-ireland/">non-US Twitter subscribers</a> will, from 18 May, see their accounts handled under Irish privacy and data protection law.&nbsp; [TNW]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>&hellip;as will <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/terms">non-US Dropbox users</a> from 1 Jun.&nbsp; [Dropbox]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>PhET offers <a href="http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2015/04/awesome-interactive-simulations-for-math-teachers.html">free interactive scientific simulations</a> covering a variety of physics and maths phenomena.&nbsp; [EducatorsTechnology]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Run a Google search from your phone and <a href="http://www.businessinsider.com/google-mobilegeddon-2015-4">Google&rsquo;s new algorithm will now favour mobile-friendly sites</a> in its rankings.&nbsp; [Stephen Downes]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>TNW suggests <a href="http://thenextweb.com/dd/2015/04/21/the-14-best-data-visualization-tools/">14 data visualization tools</a>, divided into those for techies (e.g. D3.js) and others for mere mortals (e.g. Datawrapper).&nbsp; [TNW]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Only 1% of adults in Nigeria own a landline phone.&nbsp; See more <a href="http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/03/20/10-facts-about-technology-use-emerging-world/">facts about technology use in the emerging world</a>.&nbsp; [Pew]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <a href="http://jime.open.ac.uk/collections/special/distance-learning-openness-and-educational-technology">latest issue of JIME</a> comprises invited papers from the great and the good at the OU&rsquo;s CALRG annual conference.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
<p><strong>And Finally&hellip;</strong></p>
<p><em>[Open Culture; Google; TechCrunch]</em></p>
<p>Google continues to expand its panoramic offerings.&nbsp; In addition to the <a href="http://www.googleartproject.com/">virtual art gallery</a> and Street View explorations of <a href="http://google-latlong.blogspot.co.uk/2013/09/explore-galapagos-and-be-darwin-for-day.html">the Galapagos Islands</a> and the <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2015/03/12/google-partners-with-local-nonprofit-to-bring-street-view-better-maps-to-mount-everest-region">Mount Everest region</a> (all reported in earlier digests), you can now take look around (and below the surface of) <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2015/04/20/google-brings-street-view-to-loch-ness">Loch Ness</a>.&nbsp; There&rsquo;s also an interactive tour of the <a href="http://g.co/insideabbeyroad">Abbey Road Studios</a> that lets you explore the recording studio, watch interviews and mini documentaries, and view iconic photos.&nbsp;</p>
<p>But if all that realism is a bit much, Swedish coder Einar &Ouml;berg has created <a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/brick-street-view-turns-google-maps-into-lego/">Brick Street View</a> which allows you to tour around any part of the world as if it was constructed in Lego, complete with toy cars and trees.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 15 May 2015 12:49:57 +0000</pubDate>
